<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="224" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1436,1866,2035]" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1866,1891]" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Male (
<figureCitation box="[355,446,1866,1891]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="27.[151,250,1982,2004]" captionTargetBox="[168,1416,494,1954]" captionTargetId="figure@27.[161,1427,481,1964]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 16. Ptilothyris crossoceros Meyrick. A, Lectotype, male, in NHMW; B, Labels of lectotype; C, Dorsal view of head; D, Male genitalia, gen. slide no. CIS-7104, paralectotype; E, Phallus; F, Uncus and juxta; G, Apical part of phallus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2594889/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">Figs. 16</figureCitation>
A–C). Forewing length 
<quantity box="[717,800,1867,1891]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="23" pageNumber="224" unit="mm" value="12.0">12 mm</quantity>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meyrick in Naturhistorisches Museum" authorityYear="1934" box="[812,1070,1866,1891]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Ptilothyris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crossoceros">
<emphasis box="[812,1070,1866,1891]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="224">Ptilothyris crossoceros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from other known species of the genus by the color pattern of both wings and the dorsally pale orange antenna: forewing with a more or less triangular pale orange patch medially on inner margin; hind wing fuscous, with large, deep orange in basal half, occupying from basal 1/5 to 3/5 above anal veins; the basal plate of gnathos in male genitalia convex caudally and not trifurcate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
